40|$|Common {{notions about}} {{the source of}} <b>communal</b> land <b>conflict</b> in Africa have long {{explained}} it as growing out of conditions of environmental scarcity. This article argues instead that the institutional structure {{of the legal system}} is central to understanding which countries are prone to experience <b>communal</b> land <b>conflict.</b> When competing cus-tomary and modern jurisdictions coexist in countries inhabited by mixed identity groups, the conflicting sources of legal authority lead to insecurity about which source of law will prevail. Because the source of law is contested, con-flict parties cannot trust the legal system to predictably adjudicate disputes, which encourages the use of extrajudicial vigilante measures. Using new data on communal violence in West Africa, this argument is examined for the period 1990 – 2009. The results show that in countries where competing jurisdictions exist, <b>communal</b> land <b>conflict</b> is 200 – 350 % more likely. These findings suggest that researchers should consider the role of legal institutions and processes in relation to social unrest and collective violence...|$|R
40|$|Survey {{study on}} the occurrences of {{resources}} conflicts among the Fulani‟s herdsman and arable farmers in Yewa Area, Ogun State, Nigeria were carried out with 156 well-structured questionnaires, interview and observational methods was also adopted where necessary. Results shows that 70 % were male, 86. 67 % and 13. 33 % were married and single respectively, Agbon/Ojodu was rated as very seriously attacked area; Ibeku, Asa, Iselu were very frequently affected area; while Oja-Odan, Aworo and Tobolo among others were frequently attacked. The 96. 67 % of the respondents agreed that farmland was destroyed. Loss of material resources were, however, more widespread among farmers. Income loss had the highest relative incidence (92. 4 %) among the farmers, followed by loss of yields (81 %), household resources (46. 5 %) and farm stored products (37. 3 %). On the part of Fulani‟s herdsmen, losses were minimal, 13. 6 %, 26. 7 %, 4. 1 %, and 3. 6 % of herdsmen claimed to have suffered losses in respect of their, income, yield, farm stored products and household resources respectively. Conclusively the <b>communal</b> <b>conflicts</b> affected the general production of arable farmers and Fulani‟s herdsmen, measures such as establishment of ranch for nomads and demarcation of grazing reserves for Fulani herdsmen along the routes will reduce the <b>communal</b> <b>conflicts</b> between the farmers and Fulani herdsmen...|$|R
